
Notes on Nuttx (partial) port of tinyssh
1) Download tarbal 20260301 tag found at:
   https://github.com/janmojzis/tinyssh/releases/tag/20260301

2) untar tinyssh tarball and move content of tinyssh-20260301 into nuttx-apps/netutils/tinyssh

3) Added Kconfig, Makefile, CMakeLists.txt, Make.defs.

4) Configure for a board ( nucleo-h743zi2:jumbo in mycase)

5) Build to get default flash/sram sizes:

           flash:      314180 B         2 MB     14.98%
            sram:       58288 B       512 KB     11.12%

6) make menuconfig (to change Nuttx configuration and enable tinyssh)
   Need to enable CONFIG_PSEUDOTERM (to get openpty()); found under:
   -> Device Driver
     -> Serial Driver Support
       -> Pseudo-Terminal (PTY) support
   Note: Enabling PSEUDOTERM automatically selects PIPES
         (to enable pipe() function)
   Need to enable NETUTILS_TINYSSH; found under:
   -> Application Configuration
     -> Network Utilities
       -> TinySSH server
   Note: tinyssh requires PIPE and PSEUDOTERM to be enabled first
         before tinyssh can be enabled in menuconfig.

7) Build - fails due to missing "has*.h" configuration files generated by
   original Makefiled(which attempts compilation of simple programs to
   determin if header files/API functions are available).
   To figure this out, for each hasxxx.c file, tried to compile
   using "arm-none-eabi-gcc -Wall -i $(TOPDIR)/include hasxxx.c -o /tmp/hasxxx.o"
   and if compilation succeeds, place "#define HASXXX 1" in hasxxx.h;
   else place "#undef HASXXX" in hasxxx.h.
   Repeat for:
     haslib1305.c hasmlock.c hasutmploginlogout.c hasutmpuser.c
     haslib25519.c hasopenpty.c hasutmplogwtmp.c hasutmpxaddrv6.c
     haslibntruprime.c hassetsid.c hasutmpname.c hasutmpx.c
     haslibrandombytes.c hasutilh.c hasutmppid.c hasutmpxsyslen.c
     haslibutilh.c hasutmpaddrv6.c hasutmptime.c hasutmpxupdwtmpx.c
     haslimits.c hasutmp.c hasutmptv.c hasvalgrind.c
     haslogintty.c hasutmphost.c hasutmptype.c
   Note: Add "#undef HASSETSID" in hassetsid.h (since Nuttx does not provide
         and tinyssh assumes is available)

8) Build - fails again dues to channel_exec trying to setup a terminal
   session which requires execve().
   To continue to build (to get footprint) I added
   "#ifdef TINYSSH_CREATE_TERMINAL_SESSION" and an #else clause
   to short out content of channel_exec().

9) Build - which fails due to overflowing SRAM:
   arm-none-eabi-ld: /home/peter/git/nuttx/github/tinyssh-ref/nuttx/nuttx section `.bss' will not fit in region `sram'
   arm-none-eabi-ld: region `sram' overflowed by 215252 bytes
   Memory region         Used Size  Region Size  %age Used
           flash:      388804 B         2 MB     18.54%
            sram:      739540 B       512 KB    141.06%

   This is due to default definitions of:
   PACKET_LIMIT = 32768
   PACKET_FULLLIMIT = 35000
   PACKET_RECVLIMIT = 113072
   CHANNEL_BUFSIZE = 131072   
   which makes size of following tinyssh global structures:
   sizeof(struct packet) = 413984
   sizeof(struct channel) = 131552

10) I added configuration Kconfig tinyssh values with defaults matching
   the value soriginally in channel.h/packet.h modified headers to
   define its constants in terms of corresponding Kconfg values.
   Run menuconfig and resize tinyssh values; 
   -> Application Configuration
     -> Network Utilities
       -> TinySSH server
          channel buffer size => lower to 1024
          packet limit => lower to 1024
          packet full limit => lower to 1024
          packet recv limit => lower to 1024
   Note: The above sizes selected are arbitrary; I haven't tried to
         debug to understand affect of lowering them from defaults

11) Build.
   SRAM size comes down further (but still large):
            sram:       58288 B       512 KB     11.12%
            sram:      345876 B       512 KB     65.97%


At this point need to:
1) debug to understand:
    - Impact of reducing the constants mentioned above
    - Is constructed to operate at required reduced footpront
    - Can tinyssh properly detect/recover from smaller buffers
      filling up before expected
2) Need to provide temrinal session
    - Can /dev/telent device (modified) be used to provide the terminal session?
3) Need to determine how to store/acess SSH keys (since tinyssh does not
    - ask for user/password

Should:
1) Determine if some of the functionality tinyssh provides replacements for
   if missing (e.g. any of the "haslibxxx.c" configuration test files) and
   if so what Nuttx configuration needed to provide Nuttx component instead
   as well as if the Nuttx component is sufficient to use in tinyssh.

And potentially want:
1) Determine which(if any) buffers in struct packet have exclusive lifetimes;
   perhaps some can be consolidated (i.e. if temp buffers used for key exchange
   but not used during transmission/reception of session; recycle into
   buffer used during session)

